WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.680 --> 00:00:04.911
Prof: We're now going to
start the block of the course

00:00:04.911 --> 00:00:08.828
which is on ecology,
and these are the titles of the

00:00:08.828 --> 00:00:10.470
upcoming lectures.
 

00:00:10.470 --> 00:00:13.540
You can think of ecology as
providing the theater in which

00:00:13.540 --> 00:00:16.065
the evolutionary play occurs;
that's a metaphor from Evelyn

00:00:16.065 --> 00:00:16.420
Hutchinson.
 

00:00:20.690 --> 00:00:27.800
And basically I'm doing a
top-down, and then going back;

00:00:27.800 --> 00:00:30.645
going from the top down,
and then going from the bottom

00:00:30.645 --> 00:00:32.805
back up to the top,
in going through these

00:00:32.805 --> 00:00:33.490
lectures.
 

00:00:33.490 --> 00:00:38.326
So I'm going to start today by
taking about climate and the

00:00:38.326 --> 00:00:40.890
planet,
and how life is distributed on

00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:43.483
the planet,
and then move from that into

00:00:43.483 --> 00:00:44.340
the biology.
 

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:47.673
So looking at physiological
ecology and interactions with

00:00:47.673 --> 00:00:50.867
the physical environment,
leading from that through

00:00:50.867 --> 00:00:52.946
population growth,
competition,

00:00:52.946 --> 00:00:57.864
predation, parasitism,
up to community--so that's sort

00:00:57.864 --> 00:01:03.445
of a way of doing a Cartesian
bottom up construction of

00:01:03.445 --> 00:01:07.585
communities--
and then dealing with some of

00:01:07.585 --> 00:01:10.760
the larger scale issues in
ecology,

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:13.250
which have to do with islands
and meta-populations,

00:01:13.250 --> 00:01:18.970
and then systems ecology,
energy and matter flow.

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:25.748
And then I'm going to end with
a lecture which is both about

00:01:25.748 --> 00:01:30.230
the role of biodiversity in
ecology,

00:01:30.230 --> 00:01:34.599
but also about general takes on
the value of biodiversity,

00:01:34.599 --> 00:01:38.334
and this last lecture in
ecology is going to include some

00:01:38.334 --> 00:01:41.470
stuff like an economic take on
biodiversity,

00:01:41.470 --> 00:01:43.319
an evolutionary take on
biodiversity,

00:01:43.319 --> 00:01:48.123
as well as the issue of does
biodiversity actually help

00:01:48.123 --> 00:01:50.970
ecosystems to function better?
 

00:01:50.970 --> 00:01:52.370
So that's what's coming up.
 

00:01:52.370 --> 00:01:55.587
And today we're going to
basically look at the climates

00:01:55.587 --> 00:01:58.565
of the planet,
how the planet can be looked at

00:01:58.565 --> 00:02:02.540
as a set of climate machines,
and how they generate the

00:02:02.540 --> 00:02:04.390
biomes, on the planet.
 

00:02:04.390 --> 00:02:07.888
So at this scale,
this stuff I think is probably

00:02:07.888 --> 00:02:09.229
pretty familiar.
 

00:02:09.229 --> 00:02:12.823
The world climate is of course
cold at the poles and warm at

00:02:12.823 --> 00:02:15.930
the tropics, but there's a lot
of detail in that.

00:02:15.930 --> 00:02:19.021
It tends to be warmer and
wetter on the western sides of

00:02:19.021 --> 00:02:22.566
the northern continents,
and cooler and drier on the

00:02:22.566 --> 00:02:25.720
eastern sides of the northern
continents.

00:02:25.720 --> 00:02:28.055
The influence of the Gulf
Stream can be seen pretty

00:02:28.055 --> 00:02:31.514
clearly here in Europe,
with this large warm area being

00:02:31.514 --> 00:02:35.500
sort of pushed up and to the
right by the warm water,

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:38.008
which is coming up out of the
Gulf of Mexico.

00:02:38.008 --> 00:02:41.978
And if you go far east into the
huge block of the Eurasian land

00:02:41.978 --> 00:02:45.032
mass,
you can get so far away from

00:02:45.032 --> 00:02:50.120
the effects of the ocean that
the coldest temperature,

00:02:50.120 --> 00:02:51.340
at least in the Northern
Hemisphere,

00:02:51.340 --> 00:02:53.280
was recorded right about here.
 

00:02:53.280 --> 00:02:56.860
It was, I think,
-127 Fahrenheit;

00:02:56.860 --> 00:02:58.060
which, you know, that's nippy.
 

00:03:02.389 --> 00:03:07.325
There are interesting
similarities in the climates of

00:03:07.325 --> 00:03:08.938
similar places.
 

00:03:08.938 --> 00:03:12.911
So if you look at the western
leading edge of North and South

00:03:12.911 --> 00:03:16.343
America,
and you go about as far south

00:03:16.343 --> 00:03:20.336
of the equator as north,
basically what you run into is

00:03:20.336 --> 00:03:21.590
a temperate rainforest.
 

00:03:21.590 --> 00:03:24.925
There's a temperate rainforest
that is stretching from Northern

00:03:24.925 --> 00:03:28.027
California up to Alaska,
and there's another temperate

00:03:28.027 --> 00:03:31.038
rainforest which stretches along
the coast of Chile.

00:03:31.038 --> 00:03:35.720
And these similarities in
climate have created similar

00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:39.430
biomes and similar selection
pressures,

00:03:39.430 --> 00:03:43.520
and have led to convergences in
the communities that you see in

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:44.508
these places.
 

00:03:44.508 --> 00:03:47.729
So if you really want to
understand why is it that if I

00:03:47.729 --> 00:03:51.745
am standing say in Chile,
or in part of New Zealand,

00:03:51.745 --> 00:03:56.050
or in British Columbia,
that they kind of remind me of

00:03:56.050 --> 00:03:56.870
each other?
 

00:03:56.870 --> 00:04:00.473
Even though the plants may not
be at all related,

00:04:00.473 --> 00:04:03.251
they look the same,
it feels the same,

00:04:03.251 --> 00:04:06.180
the forests have similar
structure.

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:11.913
Well you have to go back to why
the planet as a whole constructs

00:04:11.913 --> 00:04:15.098
similar climates in those
places.

00:04:15.098 --> 00:04:18.415
Part of it, at a local level,
if you're looking say at what's

00:04:18.415 --> 00:04:21.620
generating the rainforest in
Chile or what's generating the

00:04:21.620 --> 00:04:25.360
rainforest in British Columbia,
has to do with the way that

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:28.149
mountains are interacting with
atmosphere.

00:04:28.149 --> 00:04:32.161
So in both, in these
situations, you have got clouds

00:04:32.161 --> 00:04:36.961
that are coming in off of the
ocean, and they are being forced

00:04:36.961 --> 00:04:39.399
upward by a mountain range.
 

00:04:39.399 --> 00:04:43.853
And there's some very simple
physical chemistry that goes on

00:04:43.853 --> 00:04:46.269
when you force a cloud upward.
 

00:04:46.269 --> 00:04:49.750
The rising air is going to be
cooling before it condenses.

00:04:49.750 --> 00:04:52.750
Then it will condense and form
heavy clouds,

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:56.016
and they will rain out,
and as the wind is going to

00:04:56.016 --> 00:04:59.350
push them up over the top of the
mountain range,

00:04:59.350 --> 00:05:02.088
basically all the water will
leave the cloud.

00:05:02.088 --> 00:05:04.800
Well that's what's creating
that rainforest.

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:05.276
Okay?
 

00:05:05.276 --> 00:05:10.807
And the reason for that is that
cold air can't hold as much

00:05:10.807 --> 00:05:12.810
water as warm air.
 

00:05:12.810 --> 00:05:17.617
And the cooling is going on at
a rate of about 6 degrees

00:05:17.617 --> 00:05:21.990
Centigrade per kilometer of
elevation, going up.

00:05:21.990 --> 00:05:25.209
The air which was at 20,
coming in off the ocean--

00:05:25.209 --> 00:05:28.214
this is 20 degrees
Centigrade--is hitting perhaps 4

00:05:28.214 --> 00:05:30.500
degrees at the top of the
mountain--

00:05:30.500 --> 00:05:32.779
so you could think of this as
the Sierras,

00:05:32.779 --> 00:05:38.879
or the top of say the Cascades
in Oregon or Washington--

00:05:38.879 --> 00:05:40.440
and then it falls down the
other side.

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:43.300
And over here you have dry air
falling.

00:05:43.300 --> 00:05:46.146
This is wet air rising,
and it rains out,

00:05:46.146 --> 00:05:48.709
and then you have dry air
falling.

00:05:48.709 --> 00:05:51.040
And this wet air rising and
raining,

00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:54.300
and dry air falling and
warming, and ending up 4 degrees

00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:57.857
warmer at the same elevation on
this side than it was on this

00:05:57.857 --> 00:05:59.971
side,
because of the heat of

00:05:59.971 --> 00:06:03.569
condensation that's been
released by the rain here.

00:06:03.569 --> 00:06:04.810
This is something I want you to
remember,

00:06:04.810 --> 00:06:07.321
because it actually also
applies at the scale of the

00:06:07.321 --> 00:06:10.637
whole planet,
when you have very large air

00:06:10.637 --> 00:06:14.160
cells that are rotating on the
planet.

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:17.605
And where there's dry air
falling, you're going to get

00:06:17.605 --> 00:06:19.839
deserts,
and where there is warm air

00:06:19.839 --> 00:06:22.149
rising you're going to get
rainforests,

00:06:22.149 --> 00:06:25.970
whether you have the mountain
range there or not.

00:06:25.970 --> 00:06:29.233
So we'll see that in a minute,
and that's why I wanted to

00:06:29.233 --> 00:06:32.089
introduce this level of analysis
at this point.

00:06:32.089 --> 00:06:32.355
Okay?
 

00:06:32.355 --> 00:06:35.538
So this warm air falling here
is called foehn in Switzerland,

00:06:35.538 --> 00:06:38.829
and the Swiss always complain
that it gives them headaches;

00:06:38.829 --> 00:06:41.769
it's called the Santa Ana wind
in Los Angeles;

00:06:41.769 --> 00:06:45.305
and there's a special wind that
blows down the valley behind

00:06:45.305 --> 00:06:47.942
Lahaina, Maui,
that can hit 140 miles an hour

00:06:47.942 --> 00:06:49.860
sometimes, which is similar.
 

00:06:49.860 --> 00:06:53.956
So these local dry hot winds
can be very important,

00:06:53.956 --> 00:06:58.788
and they're actually what drive
the wild fires in Malibu and

00:06:58.788 --> 00:07:00.509
things like that.
 

00:07:00.509 --> 00:07:04.439
Okay, now let's take a look at
the whole planet.

00:07:04.439 --> 00:07:08.430
If the earth was simply a
stationary ball,

00:07:08.430 --> 00:07:11.607
sitting in space,
undisturbed,

00:07:11.607 --> 00:07:15.879
but was being heated at the
equator,

00:07:15.879 --> 00:07:18.620
it would develop basically two
convection cells,

00:07:18.620 --> 00:07:20.149
one in each hemisphere.
 

00:07:20.149 --> 00:07:24.528
So there would be cold air that
was falling on the poles.

00:07:24.528 --> 00:07:27.502
It would be falling down to the
surface and it would be picking

00:07:27.502 --> 00:07:30.002
up moisture and rising,
and basically you would get a

00:07:30.002 --> 00:07:31.730
belt of rainforest around the
equator,

00:07:31.730 --> 00:07:35.293
and you would have deserts at
the poles and a gradient in

00:07:35.293 --> 00:07:35.930
between.
 

00:07:35.930 --> 00:07:40.379
That would be what would happen
if the earth were not rotating.

00:07:40.379 --> 00:07:44.370
The earth is rotating,
and because it's rotating,

00:07:44.370 --> 00:07:49.410
on an idealized planet you
would get three Hadley cells,

00:07:49.410 --> 00:07:52.350
going out from the
equator--three in the north and

00:07:52.350 --> 00:07:55.954
three in the south--
and at the equator you would

00:07:55.954 --> 00:08:00.278
have warm air rising and it
would be dropping rain,

00:08:00.278 --> 00:08:03.341
because as it rose it cooled,
and it would lose capacity to

00:08:03.341 --> 00:08:05.189
hold water and it would rain
out.

00:08:05.189 --> 00:08:10.728
Then it would flow northward
and fall at about 30º

00:08:10.728 --> 00:08:11.550
north.
 

00:08:11.550 --> 00:08:13.300
Okay?
 

00:08:13.300 --> 00:08:18.360
There it would be interacting
with another similar cell that

00:08:18.360 --> 00:08:23.850
would be carrying warm air north
and rising at about 60 north.

00:08:23.850 --> 00:08:24.208
Okay?
 

00:08:24.208 --> 00:08:28.360
Remember where the rainforests
were in Chile and in British

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:32.442
Columbia;
they are in this region here

00:08:32.442 --> 00:08:35.320
and in this region here.
 

00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:38.950
And this is where the deserts
are, around the world;

00:08:38.950 --> 00:08:42.490
they're at about 30 North and
30 South.

00:08:42.490 --> 00:08:45.279
Now this is an idealized format.
 

00:08:45.279 --> 00:08:49.350
At the boundary,
by the way, of where you've got

00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:53.940
the polar highs and the northern
Hadley cell here,

00:08:53.940 --> 00:08:56.830
right at this boundary is where
you get a polar front,

00:08:56.830 --> 00:09:00.811
and this is where the jet
stream goes around the world in

00:09:00.811 --> 00:09:04.649
the north and it goes around the
world in the south.

00:09:04.649 --> 00:09:07.828
So the location of the jet
stream that drives most of the

00:09:07.828 --> 00:09:11.974
weather that we encounter here,
and the idea that it might say

00:09:11.974 --> 00:09:16.106
pull in a mass of Canadian- a
clipper of Canadian weather

00:09:16.106 --> 00:09:19.058
coming in from the polar front
here,

00:09:19.058 --> 00:09:21.480
is actually generated by this
structure,

00:09:21.480 --> 00:09:23.340
and it's wobbly.
 

00:09:23.340 --> 00:09:24.178
Okay?
 

00:09:24.178 --> 00:09:27.105
In an idealized world this is
all smooth, and these lines are

00:09:27.105 --> 00:09:28.080
clean and whatnot.
 

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:30.371
But, in fact,
the surface of the planet has

00:09:30.371 --> 00:09:33.410
got stuff on it,
like continents and oceans,

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:37.340
and as this stuff moves in its
circulation pattern,

00:09:37.340 --> 00:09:41.250
both north and south,
and west to east,

00:09:41.250 --> 00:09:43.740
around the Northern Hemisphere,
it wobbles,

00:09:43.740 --> 00:09:46.407
because it's been deflected by
local perturbations like

00:09:46.407 --> 00:09:47.840
mountain ranges and oceans.
 

00:09:51.899 --> 00:09:57.666
So out of this you get patterns
of wind that in fact have--well

00:09:57.666 --> 00:10:02.408
now but they not only currently
generate weather.

00:10:02.408 --> 00:10:07.346
You can really only understand
say the history of the last 8 or

00:10:07.346 --> 00:10:11.326
10,000 years of human
civilization on the planet by

00:10:11.326 --> 00:10:15.149
realizing that the people who
were trading,

00:10:15.149 --> 00:10:20.265
and were using boats to move,
were relying on the fact that

00:10:20.265 --> 00:10:22.509
at about 35,
40º north,

00:10:22.509 --> 00:10:25.822
you can count on a west wind;
at about 20º

00:10:25.822 --> 00:10:29.028
north you can count on a trade
wind;

00:10:29.028 --> 00:10:31.269
and that repeats in the
Southern Hemisphere.

00:10:31.269 --> 00:10:35.493
And this is actually--these
trades here, over in the Indian

00:10:35.493 --> 00:10:39.788
Ocean, were what drove the trade
between India and the Roman

00:10:39.788 --> 00:10:41.500
Empire;
things like that.

00:10:44.860 --> 00:10:48.413
So you should think of the
planet as being covered

00:10:48.413 --> 00:10:51.460
with--these are really very thin
sheets.

00:10:51.460 --> 00:10:52.701
When you think,
for example,

00:10:52.701 --> 00:10:55.230
that we're looking here
probably at 3 or 4000 miles,

00:10:55.230 --> 00:11:00.048
4 or 5000 kilometers,
and the depth of this cell is

00:11:00.048 --> 00:11:04.000
actually only about 5 to 10
kilometers.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:10.000
So it's a very thin cell,
which is rotating like that.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:13.226
Now if there weren't any
continents, you'd end up with

00:11:13.226 --> 00:11:15.480
something that looked like
Jupiter.

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:19.610
Okay, Jupiter has these nice
neat bands that go around,

00:11:19.610 --> 00:11:24.269
and it is a bit--it's not the
perfect,

00:11:24.269 --> 00:11:27.149
smooth Hadley cell picture that
I was showing you,

00:11:27.149 --> 00:11:29.779
but still that's quite a tight
band there.

00:11:29.779 --> 00:11:31.700
And these are rotating cells.
 

00:11:31.700 --> 00:11:32.830
Jupiter's bigger.
 

00:11:32.830 --> 00:11:36.320
It's got a few more of them
than the earth does.

00:11:36.320 --> 00:11:40.397
The earth, by the way,
sitting on this picture is--oh,

00:11:40.397 --> 00:11:42.090
it's about that big.
 

00:11:42.090 --> 00:11:43.379
&gt;
 

00:11:43.379 --> 00:11:44.429
So this is a lot bigger.
 

00:11:47.580 --> 00:11:51.386
Because the earth has the
continents and the oceans,

00:11:51.386 --> 00:11:55.418
you don't get that smooth
picture in a shot from space,

00:11:55.418 --> 00:11:57.360
looking at the clouds.
 

00:11:57.360 --> 00:12:01.667
You see a lot of swirls and
vortexes that are being caused

00:12:01.667 --> 00:12:04.009
by these local perturbations.
 

00:12:04.009 --> 00:12:07.039
Right here you've got the
African continent coming down;

00:12:07.039 --> 00:12:09.139
you've got Antarctica down here.
 

00:12:09.139 --> 00:12:16.610
This is 40 to 60 south;
clear ocean all the way around

00:12:16.610 --> 00:12:19.480
the planet;
winds blowing in this direction;

00:12:19.480 --> 00:12:22.277
they can go all the way around
the planet with unobstructed

00:12:22.277 --> 00:12:25.267
ocean, just about the whole way,
except maybe just from the tip

00:12:25.267 --> 00:12:26.278
of South America.
 

00:12:26.278 --> 00:12:30.870
This is where you can get open
ocean waves that are up to 100

00:12:30.870 --> 00:12:32.629
feet, 30 meters high.
 

00:12:32.629 --> 00:12:34.201
And, of course,
this is also where the

00:12:34.201 --> 00:12:36.070
Whitbread Round the World race
goes down,

00:12:36.070 --> 00:12:39.845
so that people can go really
fast around the globe and take

00:12:39.845 --> 00:12:43.230
their life in their hands in
pretty rough weather.

00:12:43.230 --> 00:12:47.841
So the earth doesn't really
have the idealized model of

00:12:47.841 --> 00:12:52.538
climate that I've shown you in
the previous pictures.

00:12:52.538 --> 00:12:54.917
It's more chaotic,
but there's still a pattern

00:12:54.917 --> 00:12:57.566
there;
and I want to emphasize now

00:12:57.566 --> 00:12:59.379
some of the patterns.
 

00:12:59.379 --> 00:13:00.940
So, of course,
heat's being moved.

00:13:00.940 --> 00:13:04.759
Basically what's going on is
that heat's being moved from the

00:13:04.759 --> 00:13:06.975
equator,
towards the poles,

00:13:06.975 --> 00:13:10.090
simply by physical chemical
forces,

00:13:10.090 --> 00:13:13.250
to try to equalize the heat
gradient that's coming in from

00:13:13.250 --> 00:13:16.219
the sun,
and that's done by wind and by

00:13:16.219 --> 00:13:16.769
water.
 

00:13:16.769 --> 00:13:21.725
Now as a packet of air or water
moves towards the poles,

00:13:21.725 --> 00:13:25.418
it's coming with higher radio
velocity.

00:13:25.418 --> 00:13:29.509
Just think about the difference
in the diameter of the spinning

00:13:29.509 --> 00:13:32.149
earth at the equator and at the
poles.

00:13:32.149 --> 00:13:39.332
At the equator the diameter of
the planet is roughly 8000

00:13:39.332 --> 00:13:42.591
miles;
so the radius is about 4000

00:13:42.591 --> 00:13:43.168
miles.
 

00:13:43.168 --> 00:13:47.221
And as you move a packet of air
or water up towards the pole,

00:13:47.221 --> 00:13:50.798
by the time it gets to the
pole, the diameter is 0.

00:13:50.798 --> 00:13:51.188
Okay?
 

00:13:51.188 --> 00:13:55.866
So in between--basically it's a
trigonometric function that's

00:13:55.866 --> 00:14:00.621
telling you what's the diameter
of the spinning object as I go

00:14:00.621 --> 00:14:01.480
north.
 

00:14:01.480 --> 00:14:04.919
So if I'm coming from the
equator, and I'm headed north,

00:14:04.919 --> 00:14:08.485
I have more angular momentum
than the ground under my feet

00:14:08.485 --> 00:14:10.048
that I'm moving onto.
 

00:14:10.048 --> 00:14:13.700
It's moving slower to the east
than I am moving.

00:14:13.700 --> 00:14:17.490
And if I'm standing at the
poles and I start going south,

00:14:17.490 --> 00:14:20.946
the ground under my feet is
staring to move out from under

00:14:20.946 --> 00:14:23.556
me,
because I don't have as much

00:14:23.556 --> 00:14:25.000
angular momentum.
 

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:31.032
So what that will do is it will
take a packet of air or water

00:14:31.032 --> 00:14:35.620
that moves toward the equator,
it's coming down with lower

00:14:35.620 --> 00:14:39.428
radial velocity,
and it will be accelerated to

00:14:39.428 --> 00:14:40.450
the west.
 

00:14:40.450 --> 00:14:43.962
That apparent force--and by the
way, so going north you'll be

00:14:43.962 --> 00:14:46.323
accelerated eastward;
coming south you'll be

00:14:46.323 --> 00:14:48.629
accelerated westward,
in the Northern Hemisphere.

00:14:48.629 --> 00:14:50.100
This is an apparent force.
 

00:14:50.100 --> 00:14:50.427
Okay?
 

00:14:50.427 --> 00:14:54.422
It's called the Coriolis force,
and it's shaping the direction

00:14:54.422 --> 00:14:57.827
of major ocean currents,
and it's also shaping things

00:14:57.827 --> 00:15:00.620
like the trade winds;
and you'll see in a minute that

00:15:00.620 --> 00:15:02.029
it shapes the way that
hurricanes spin.

00:15:05.080 --> 00:15:09.115
So I'd like you to take just--I
want to make sure that you get

00:15:09.115 --> 00:15:11.696
this, and I'm going to ask,
in a minute,

00:15:11.696 --> 00:15:13.879
if one of you can explain it.
 

00:15:13.879 --> 00:15:14.153
Okay?
 

00:15:14.153 --> 00:15:17.450
So can you just take a minute
and explain it to your partner,

00:15:17.450 --> 00:15:20.470
how the Coriolis force works,
and what's really going on

00:15:20.470 --> 00:15:21.019
here.
 

00:15:21.019 --> 00:15:24.190
It's a piece of
three-dimensional geometry,

00:15:24.190 --> 00:15:27.667
and basically it's driven by
the fact that the earth is

00:15:27.667 --> 00:15:31.532
spinning on its axis and things
are moving north and south on

00:15:31.532 --> 00:15:33.399
the surface of this ball.
 

00:15:33.399 --> 00:15:34.870
Okay?
 

00:15:34.870 --> 00:15:36.120
 One or two minutes.
 

