00:17:47.299 --> 00:17:49.920
Okay, here's the planet.
 

00:17:49.920 --> 00:17:53.000
Here's the north/south axis of
the planet.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.328
Here's the equator.
 

00:17:56.328 --> 00:18:01.876
The circumference of the earth
at the equator is about 24,000

00:18:01.876 --> 00:18:04.057
miles,
and the earth is turning around

00:18:04.057 --> 00:18:06.962
once per day,
which means that a packet of

00:18:06.962 --> 00:18:09.617
air or water,
which is sitting at the

00:18:09.617 --> 00:18:13.019
equator, is moving east at about
1000 miles per hour.

00:18:16.690 --> 00:18:18.890
We're going to ship it north.
 

00:18:18.890 --> 00:18:19.538
Okay?
 

00:18:19.538 --> 00:18:21.950
It's going to be carrying heat
toward the pole.

00:18:25.318 --> 00:18:31.125
We choose a convenient spot to
take another slice of the earth

00:18:31.125 --> 00:18:36.358
where the circumference of the
earth is 12,000 miles.

00:18:36.358 --> 00:18:42.519
This chunk of ground is moving
at 500 miles per hour.

00:18:42.519 --> 00:18:46.130
So as this pack of air goes
north, the ground underneath it,

00:18:46.130 --> 00:18:49.422
by the time it's gotten up
here, is going 500 miles per

00:18:49.422 --> 00:18:51.383
hour,
towards the east,

00:18:51.383 --> 00:18:53.029
slower than it is.
 

00:18:53.029 --> 00:18:58.574
So what it does is it overtakes
the ground that's underneath it,

00:18:58.574 --> 00:19:00.950
and it bends to the east.
 

00:19:00.950 --> 00:19:02.880
Okay?
 

00:19:02.880 --> 00:19:04.630
And you can just play that back
and forth in your head.

00:19:04.630 --> 00:19:05.910
You can go from the north to
the south.

00:19:05.910 --> 00:19:07.588
You can do it in the Southern
Hemisphere;

00:19:07.588 --> 00:19:10.539
it'll work in the other
direction.

00:19:10.539 --> 00:19:11.329
Any questions on that?
 

00:19:15.528 --> 00:19:17.728
In order to see it,
you actually have to break the

00:19:17.728 --> 00:19:19.952
motion of the planet down,
in your head,

00:19:19.952 --> 00:19:24.000
and put yourself in the shoes
of something which is moving

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:27.210
north or south,
and essentially what happens is

00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:30.450
at the ground you either exceed
the speed of the ground

00:19:30.450 --> 00:19:32.818
underneath you,
or the ground goes out from

00:19:32.818 --> 00:19:36.880
under your feet,
if you're going south.

00:19:36.880 --> 00:19:39.990
So that's basically the
Coriolis force.

00:19:39.990 --> 00:19:41.880
I once had to explain this in
German,

00:19:41.880 --> 00:19:46.644
and I was just learning German,
and instead of saying "the

00:19:46.644 --> 00:19:49.304
earth spins",
which is okay in English,

00:19:49.304 --> 00:19:51.308
I said, "die Erde
spinnt" in German,

00:19:51.308 --> 00:19:53.240
which means that the world is
crazy.

00:19:53.240 --> 00:19:55.808
They loved it.
 

00:19:55.808 --> 00:19:59.000
It was totally wrong,
but they loved it.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:04.558
Okay, the result of this is
that if these motions--

00:20:04.558 --> 00:20:07.096
you know, so here you've got
the Coriolis Force taking the

00:20:07.096 --> 00:20:09.190
Kuroshio Current and bending it
to the east,

00:20:09.190 --> 00:20:11.470
as it goes north,
and then when it comes down the

00:20:11.470 --> 00:20:13.368
West Coast as the California
Current,

00:20:13.368 --> 00:20:17.623
it gets bent to the west,
and in each of the hemispheres

00:20:17.623 --> 00:20:22.338
you establish a rotation in the
ocean that looks like this.

00:20:22.338 --> 00:20:25.319
Here in the south you have
water which is flowing north;

00:20:25.319 --> 00:20:27.440
it's getting bent to the west.
 

00:20:27.440 --> 00:20:30.278
You've got water flowing to the
south, it's getting bent to the

00:20:30.278 --> 00:20:30.598
east.
 

00:20:30.598 --> 00:20:34.958
So you get counter-clockwise in
the Southern Hemisphere and

00:20:34.958 --> 00:20:37.890
clockwise in the Northern
Hemisphere.

00:20:37.890 --> 00:20:40.650
Now on top of this,
just as I showed you for the

00:20:40.650 --> 00:20:43.644
Hadley cells in the atmosphere,
there's an important

00:20:43.644 --> 00:20:46.640
three-dimensional cell structure
in the oceans.

00:20:46.640 --> 00:20:50.791
So north of the Antarctic
continent there's a place where

00:20:50.791 --> 00:20:54.868
the cold surface water of the
Antarctic gets- sinks,

00:20:54.868 --> 00:20:57.204
at the Antarctic
convergence--it's down about

00:20:57.204 --> 00:20:59.506
here--
and it then forms a cell which

00:20:59.506 --> 00:21:03.384
creeps along the floors of the
major oceans and then comes back

00:21:03.384 --> 00:21:03.759
up.
 

00:21:07.358 --> 00:21:11.874
There's a very important spot
where water from the Arctic

00:21:11.874 --> 00:21:16.146
Ocean, coming down from
Greenland, is sinking near the

00:21:16.146 --> 00:21:17.838
Gulf Stream here.
 

00:21:17.838 --> 00:21:21.230
And it's one of the real
current issues in global warming

00:21:21.230 --> 00:21:24.318
as to whether or not this point
up here or this--

00:21:24.318 --> 00:21:28.587
actually it's not a point--this
whole sheet of sinking water is

00:21:28.587 --> 00:21:30.308
going to remain stable.
 

00:21:30.308 --> 00:21:32.759
Because if it doesn't remain
stable,

00:21:32.759 --> 00:21:36.055
and this moves south,
then the Gulf Stream will get

00:21:36.055 --> 00:21:39.773
blocked and basically England,
France and Spain are going to

00:21:39.773 --> 00:21:42.916
end up with a climate which is
like that of Northern Canada;

00:21:42.916 --> 00:21:43.769
very quickly.
 

00:21:43.769 --> 00:21:48.250
That is something that could
happen in a couple of years,

00:21:48.250 --> 00:21:49.930
if this thing tips.
 

00:21:49.930 --> 00:21:53.685
So understanding that kind of
movement actually has big

00:21:53.685 --> 00:21:56.236
implications,
for society and for the people

00:21:56.236 --> 00:21:58.771
who live in these places,
who are in the hundreds of

00:21:58.771 --> 00:21:59.250
millions.
 

00:22:02.509 --> 00:22:05.142
Now there are just--I want to
show you two things about the

00:22:05.142 --> 00:22:05.960
general pattern.
 

00:22:05.960 --> 00:22:09.750
This is just repeating the
overall pattern on the planet.

00:22:09.750 --> 00:22:13.329
We get hurricanes roughly where
there are trade winds,

00:22:13.329 --> 00:22:17.046
and we get them both in the
Northern and in the Southern

00:22:17.046 --> 00:22:18.058
Hemisphere.
 

00:22:18.058 --> 00:22:21.291
And then right at the equator
we get El Niño,

00:22:21.291 --> 00:22:22.368
in the Pacific.
 

00:22:22.368 --> 00:22:24.618
And I want to show you a little
bit about hurricanes and a

00:22:24.618 --> 00:22:27.888
little bit about El Niño,
because those are two of the

00:22:27.888 --> 00:22:31.464
sort of large-scale weather
patterns that occur on the

00:22:31.464 --> 00:22:32.140
planet.
 

00:22:32.140 --> 00:22:34.586
So this question here:
Why do cyclones turn

00:22:34.586 --> 00:22:37.324
counter-clockwise in the
Northern Hemisphere and

00:22:37.324 --> 00:22:40.380
clockwise in the Southern,
is a bit puzzling,

00:22:40.380 --> 00:22:44.617
because I have just shown you
that if you take a packet of air

00:22:44.617 --> 00:22:48.837
or water and you ship it north,
it's going to result in a

00:22:48.837 --> 00:22:52.915
clockwise circulation in the
north and a counter-clockwise

00:22:52.915 --> 00:22:54.920
circulation in the south.
 

00:22:54.920 --> 00:22:57.900
And yet here is a nice photo
from space of Hurricane Katrina

00:22:57.900 --> 00:23:00.828
starting to go over Florida,
before it hits New Orleans;

00:23:00.828 --> 00:23:03.798
Cyclone Larry,
equally destructive,

00:23:03.798 --> 00:23:06.769
plowing into Northern
Australia.

00:23:06.769 --> 00:23:09.952
And you can see quite clearly
that Hurricane Katrina is

00:23:09.952 --> 00:23:12.960
counter-clockwise and Cyclone
Larry is clockwise.

00:23:12.960 --> 00:23:16.618
And that looks puzzling,
but here's the answer.

00:23:16.618 --> 00:23:19.890
If you take a standard packet
of air,

00:23:19.890 --> 00:23:21.838
moving south in the Northern
Hemisphere,

00:23:21.838 --> 00:23:24.440
hitting something like
Hurricane Katrina,

00:23:24.440 --> 00:23:27.349
it will come down and it will
take this low,

00:23:27.349 --> 00:23:30.180
and it will spin it.
 

00:23:30.180 --> 00:23:35.042
And if you have this as a set
of clockwise forces,

00:23:35.042 --> 00:23:38.615
operating on a low,
they will spin it

00:23:38.615 --> 00:23:40.798
counter-clockwise.
 

00:23:40.798 --> 00:23:44.382
And the same thing operating in
the Southern Hemisphere will

00:23:44.382 --> 00:23:47.842
spin a cyclone in the Southern
Hemisphere into a clockwise

00:23:47.842 --> 00:23:48.450
shape.
 

00:23:48.450 --> 00:23:53.220
So really it's an interesting
problem of figure and ground,

00:23:53.220 --> 00:23:55.338
or just what perspective are
you standing in,

00:23:55.338 --> 00:23:57.871
when you're trying to figure
out why the thing is spinning

00:23:57.871 --> 00:23:58.358
that way.
 

00:23:58.358 --> 00:24:04.178
Because basically it is being
operated on by external Coriolis

00:24:04.178 --> 00:24:09.519
forces that are generating the
antagonistic movement,

00:24:09.519 --> 00:24:12.480
the unexpected movement in the
structure,

00:24:12.480 --> 00:24:16.123
but it results in very
important consequences for

00:24:16.123 --> 00:24:20.068
anybody that's in the path of
one of these things.

00:24:20.068 --> 00:24:24.133
So that's basically the
explanation of why we see a

00:24:24.133 --> 00:24:28.440
counter-intuitive kind of spin
on these big storms.

00:24:28.440 --> 00:24:30.068
Now about El Niño.
 

00:24:30.068 --> 00:24:33.432
I think El Niño actually
is an extremely interesting and

00:24:33.432 --> 00:24:34.410
neat phenomenon.
 

00:24:34.410 --> 00:24:37.943
It has huge implications,
and it drives weather patterns

00:24:37.943 --> 00:24:43.470
in fact over much of the planet;
not just at the equator.

00:24:43.470 --> 00:24:48.417
Under normal conditions
basically what's going on is

00:24:48.417 --> 00:24:52.327
that you have these,
the Kuroshio Current in the

00:24:52.327 --> 00:24:54.775
northern Pacific,
which is coming down off of

00:24:54.775 --> 00:24:58.258
California and Mexico,
and then going west along the

00:24:58.258 --> 00:24:58.990
equator.
 

00:24:58.990 --> 00:25:01.288
You've got the Humboldt Current
in the southern Pacific,

00:25:01.288 --> 00:25:03.884
which is coming north,
along the coast of Chile and

00:25:03.884 --> 00:25:05.957
Peru,
and then curving out to the

00:25:05.957 --> 00:25:09.270
west, driven in those big
clockwise Northern Hemisphere

00:25:09.270 --> 00:25:12.769
gyres and counter-clockwise
Southern Hemisphere gyres.

00:25:12.769 --> 00:25:18.078
And what they're doing--because
they have a continent more or

00:25:18.078 --> 00:25:22.029
less to the right here--
they are picking up the water

00:25:22.029 --> 00:25:25.470
and shoving it offshore,
and that's causing the lower

00:25:25.470 --> 00:25:29.373
bottom water to well up,
and they are shoving the warm

00:25:29.373 --> 00:25:31.598
surface water out to the west.
 

00:25:31.598 --> 00:25:35.662
And that causes a big buildup
of warm water,

00:25:35.662 --> 00:25:39.631
which is out about at Guam in
the Marianas,

00:25:39.631 --> 00:25:43.598
so--or all the way to the
Philippines.

00:25:43.598 --> 00:25:47.871
And this pile of warm water is
actually about a meter higher

00:25:47.871 --> 00:25:50.838
than the water in the eastern
Pacific,

00:25:50.838 --> 00:25:53.970
and it's being held there by
the currents and the winds.

00:25:53.970 --> 00:25:56.806
So it's actually,
over a distance of about 7 or

00:25:56.806 --> 00:25:59.441
8000 miles,
it's picking the surface of the

00:25:59.441 --> 00:26:02.299
ocean up and it's stacking it up
a meter higher,

00:26:02.299 --> 00:26:04.630
out to the west, in the Pacific.
 

00:26:04.630 --> 00:26:07.618
Now under El Niño
conditions,

00:26:07.618 --> 00:26:10.410
what happens is that the
currents break down,

00:26:10.410 --> 00:26:13.454
and when the currents break
down, the force that was holding

00:26:13.454 --> 00:26:16.140
the water higher in the western
Pacific goes away.

00:26:16.140 --> 00:26:17.670
And what does the water do?
 

00:26:17.670 --> 00:26:22.182
It falls downhill,
it flows back to the eastern

00:26:22.182 --> 00:26:27.969
Pacific, covering the eastern
Pacific up with a layer of hot

00:26:27.969 --> 00:26:28.950
water.
 

00:26:28.950 --> 00:26:31.358
This has all kinds of
consequences.

00:26:31.358 --> 00:26:36.833
One of the consequences is that
warm water evaporates more than

00:26:36.833 --> 00:26:40.267
cold water,
and so rainfall increases,

00:26:40.267 --> 00:26:44.935
in the eastern Pacific,
and cells that carry a lot of

00:26:44.935 --> 00:26:50.490
water will then get blown into
places like Mexico and Arizona.

00:26:50.490 --> 00:26:53.571
And during El Niño
conditions you'll get much

00:26:53.571 --> 00:26:56.048
heavier rainfall in the American
West,

00:26:56.048 --> 00:26:58.759
and all the way through to the
Mississippi Valley,

00:26:58.759 --> 00:27:01.960
than you will during normal
conditions.

00:27:01.960 --> 00:27:04.910
But another very important
thing happens.

00:27:04.910 --> 00:27:07.558
This covers up the upwelling.
 

00:27:07.558 --> 00:27:09.655
It covers up the cold water
that was coming up from the

00:27:09.655 --> 00:27:12.201
bottom of the ocean,
and that cold water that was

00:27:12.201 --> 00:27:15.801
coming up from the bottom of the
ocean is carrying with it all

00:27:15.801 --> 00:27:17.160
kinds of fertilizer.
 

00:27:17.160 --> 00:27:20.227
Basically the bottom of the
ocean has been receiving the

00:27:20.227 --> 00:27:23.294
dead bodies of algae and
zooplankton and everything else

00:27:23.294 --> 00:27:24.410
for a long time.
 

00:27:24.410 --> 00:27:27.596
There's been a lot of nitrogen
and phosphate building up down

00:27:27.596 --> 00:27:30.464
there, and under normal
conditions that's being carried

00:27:30.464 --> 00:27:31.740
up by the upwelling.
 

00:27:31.740 --> 00:27:34.832
And when El Niño rolls
in, it covers it up,

00:27:34.832 --> 00:27:37.230
turns off the fertilization
process.

00:27:37.230 --> 00:27:40.636
The alga production goes down,
zooplankton production goes

00:27:40.636 --> 00:27:43.923
down, the fish don't have so
much to eat and the fishery

00:27:43.923 --> 00:27:45.118
stocks collapse.
 

00:27:45.118 --> 00:27:48.118
So once every ten or eleven
years,

00:27:48.118 --> 00:27:52.519
when this happens,
the great fisheries of the

00:27:52.519 --> 00:27:56.858
Eastern Pacific collapse,
and that means that thousands

00:27:56.858 --> 00:28:01.400
of fishermen go out of work;
it means that sea birds starve.

00:28:01.400 --> 00:28:05.641
And you should think of the
whole Pacific Ocean as kind of

00:28:05.641 --> 00:28:10.180
ringing like a bell on about a
ten or eleven year interval.

00:28:10.180 --> 00:28:13.383
And since the Pacific Ocean
occupies roughly half the

00:28:13.383 --> 00:28:15.711
planet,
that means there are signatures

00:28:15.711 --> 00:28:18.859
of this that reverberate all the
way around the planet,

00:28:18.859 --> 00:28:22.140
on about a ten year interval.
 

00:28:22.140 --> 00:28:23.635
When I was doing my Ph.D.
 

00:28:23.635 --> 00:28:26.390
on the evolution of mosquito
fish in Hawaii,

00:28:26.390 --> 00:28:30.653
I had sixty years of records of
the level of sugar plantation

00:28:30.653 --> 00:28:33.862
reservoirs in Hawaii,
and I did a time series

00:28:33.862 --> 00:28:37.650
analysis on it and I picked up
two very dominant signals.

00:28:37.650 --> 00:28:40.021
There was a short frequency
signal, which was the

00:28:40.021 --> 00:28:42.838
weekends--that's when people
went home on the weekends;

00:28:42.838 --> 00:28:45.779
so the reservoirs didn't
fluctuate on the weekends.

00:28:45.779 --> 00:28:48.874
But there was an eleven-year
signal that was El Niño,

00:28:48.874 --> 00:28:51.759
and it was the biggest,
strongest signal in the data.

00:28:51.759 --> 00:28:53.689
So up in Hawaii,
which is really quite a ways

00:28:53.689 --> 00:28:54.580
away--
on this map,

00:28:54.580 --> 00:28:58.192
Hawaii would be up off the map,
up here somewhere--this is

00:28:58.192 --> 00:29:02.598
making a big impact on the
ten-year rainfall record,

00:29:02.598 --> 00:29:06.460
and it's doing so in Arizona
and New Mexico and Texas,

00:29:06.460 --> 00:29:09.390
and California as well.
 

00:29:09.390 --> 00:29:11.210
Okay, so that's El Niño.
 

00:29:11.210 --> 00:29:12.868
And to see what it looks like.
 

00:29:12.868 --> 00:29:17.365
This is a NOA picture of the
temperature of the Pacific,

00:29:17.365 --> 00:29:22.269
going from the eastern Pacific
out to the western Pacific.

00:29:22.269 --> 00:29:23.519
And these are different years.
 

00:29:23.519 --> 00:29:27.470
So this is starting in 1986 and
going up to 2001,

00:29:27.470 --> 00:29:30.318
and this year,
right here, where you see a big

00:29:30.318 --> 00:29:33.535
tongue of warm water,
29º Centigrade,

00:29:33.535 --> 00:29:38.618
pushing all the way back in to
the eastern Pacific is 1997;

00:29:38.618 --> 00:29:41.130
one of the major El Niño
events.

00:29:41.130 --> 00:29:42.605
And, in fact,
there is right now,

00:29:42.605 --> 00:29:45.509
I think in the last year or so,
another El Niño event.

00:29:45.509 --> 00:29:46.470
Yes, Myra?
 

00:29:46.470 --> 00:29:50.710
Student: 
&gt;

00:29:50.710 --> 00:29:54.482
Prof: There appears to
have been this kind of cyclicity

00:29:54.482 --> 00:29:58.380
in the Pacific for as long back
as we can see in the records.

00:29:58.380 --> 00:30:01.582
I think that the things that
would probably make it break

00:30:01.582 --> 00:30:03.470
down are plate tectonic events.
 

00:30:03.470 --> 00:30:06.632
I do not know if El Niño
was regular before the Isthmus

00:30:06.632 --> 00:30:09.068
of Panama formed about ten
million years ago.

00:30:09.068 --> 00:30:09.869
I suspect it would've been
different.

00:30:14.430 --> 00:30:17.588
And this is just that--this is
the actual temperature,

00:30:17.588 --> 00:30:20.509
and then this is the deviation
from the normal.

00:30:20.509 --> 00:30:23.208
And, by the way,
they call a year that's sort of

00:30:23.208 --> 00:30:25.390
really super normal,
La Niña.

00:30:25.390 --> 00:30:28.073
So this is a La Niña and
this is El Niño,

00:30:28.073 --> 00:30:28.670
down here.
 

00:30:28.670 --> 00:30:30.724
So you should think of La
Niña as being cold water

00:30:30.724 --> 00:30:33.509
in the eastern Pacific,
and El Niño as being hot

00:30:33.509 --> 00:30:45.940
water in the eastern Pacific,
with all of its consequences.

00:30:45.940 --> 00:30:47.799
In La Niña you've got
the upwelling going,

00:30:47.799 --> 00:30:49.390
and in El Niño it's
interrupted;

00:30:49.390 --> 00:30:52.993
and of course that would be
happening basically right along

00:30:52.993 --> 00:30:53.430
here.
 

00:30:53.430 --> 00:30:56.943
But upwelling is normal in much
of the planet,

00:30:56.943 --> 00:30:59.990
and it happens along coastal
margins.

00:30:59.990 --> 00:31:04.528
So the areas here that are
indicated in red is where cold,

00:31:04.528 --> 00:31:08.450
deep water is being moved to
the surface by various forces,

00:31:08.450 --> 00:31:11.480
and in the process is
fertilizing the surface layer,

00:31:11.480 --> 00:31:14.157
and that's driving the
productivity of the world's

00:31:14.157 --> 00:31:14.650
oceans.
 

00:31:14.650 --> 00:31:18.680
So people, of course,
have discovered this;

00:31:18.680 --> 00:31:21.474
I mean, one could have made a
theoretical argument,

00:31:21.474 --> 00:31:24.436
but in fact the world's
fishermen discovered this long

00:31:24.436 --> 00:31:26.730
before there was any climatic
theory.

00:31:26.730 --> 00:31:30.490
And the greatest productivity
in the world's oceans are in

00:31:30.490 --> 00:31:33.592
places like the North Sea,
the Benguela Current,

00:31:33.592 --> 00:31:37.700
and the West Coast of Africa;
the coast of Peru with its

00:31:37.700 --> 00:31:41.306
gigantic anchovy fishery;
West Coast of North America

00:31:41.306 --> 00:31:44.098
with tuna and sardines and
things like that;

00:31:44.098 --> 00:31:48.236
and you can see a few other
spots around the world that are

00:31:48.236 --> 00:31:49.519
very productive.
 

00:31:49.519 --> 00:31:50.720
Fishing is mighty good in New
Zealand.

00:31:54.068 --> 00:31:57.557
The way this works is through a
combination of offshore winds

00:31:57.557 --> 00:31:59.009
and the Coriolis force.
 

00:31:59.009 --> 00:32:01.480
So let's first do the offshore
wind.

00:32:01.480 --> 00:32:05.790
If you have any body of land,
and you have wind blowing

00:32:05.790 --> 00:32:08.782
offshore,
it pushes the surface water

00:32:08.782 --> 00:32:13.151
off, and just in order for
gravity to equilibrate the water

00:32:13.151 --> 00:32:16.787
pressure,
it's going to therefore pull up

00:32:16.787 --> 00:32:19.358
deep water at the shore line.
 

00:32:19.358 --> 00:32:24.390
And if any of you live on the
West Coast,

00:32:24.390 --> 00:32:26.650
I think you know this perfectly
well,

00:32:26.650 --> 00:32:31.517
because you know that very
often the water on the shoreline

00:32:31.517 --> 00:32:35.210
of the West Coast is colder than
the air,

00:32:35.210 --> 00:32:37.980
and it is going to produce fog.
 

00:32:37.980 --> 00:32:41.598
And all the way from roughly
Santa Barbara up to Juneau,

00:32:41.598 --> 00:32:44.823
you have fog banks,
which is because you have cold

00:32:44.823 --> 00:32:48.378
water hitting warm air;
it's that cold upwelling water

00:32:48.378 --> 00:32:50.868
hitting the warm air that makes
the fog,

00:32:50.868 --> 00:32:55.029
which is so characteristic of
the West Coast of the United

00:32:55.029 --> 00:32:56.953
States,
and is also characteristic,

00:32:56.953 --> 00:33:00.940
by the way,
of the West Coast of Namibia.

00:33:00.940 --> 00:33:03.901
There are even some beetles
that live in the desert of

00:33:03.901 --> 00:33:07.588
Namibia that are specialized for
catching the fog on their feet.

00:33:07.588 --> 00:33:10.974
They stand on their heads and
they put their feet up and they

00:33:10.974 --> 00:33:14.021
catch water with their feet,
because it doesn't rain in

00:33:14.021 --> 00:33:14.700
Namibia.
 

00:33:14.700 --> 00:33:19.273
Now if we were to look at say
the coast of Oregon,

00:33:19.273 --> 00:33:24.130
and we have wind or current
which is coming south;

00:33:24.130 --> 00:33:27.440
we're in the Northern
Hemisphere, we're going south.

00:33:27.440 --> 00:33:30.898
The Coriolis force is working,
and because we're coming south

00:33:30.898 --> 00:33:33.707
we're going to be--
we have less angular momentum

00:33:33.707 --> 00:33:36.959
than the earth under our feet,
and therefore it's going to be

00:33:36.959 --> 00:33:38.250
diverted out to the west.
 

00:33:38.250 --> 00:33:41.588
That means that there's going
to be a tendency for the

00:33:41.588 --> 00:33:44.108
Coriolis force to suck water
offshore.

00:33:44.108 --> 00:33:46.868
And the wind or the current
could be coming south,

00:33:46.868 --> 00:33:51.093
but the net vector of movement
of surface water will be

00:33:51.093 --> 00:33:55.009
deflected off to the right,
by the Coriolis force,

00:33:55.009 --> 00:33:58.163
and pulled offshore,
and so you're going to get cold

00:33:58.163 --> 00:34:01.462
bottom water,
welling up to the surface and

00:34:01.462 --> 00:34:03.210
fertilizing things.
 

00:34:03.210 --> 00:34:08.239
Okay, that's a little bit about
how the climate machine is

00:34:08.239 --> 00:34:10.268
working in the ocean.
 

00:34:10.268 --> 00:34:14.320
Now let's take a minute to look
at what it's doing to the biomes

00:34:14.320 --> 00:34:18.112
on the surface of the planet,
on the terrestrial part of the

00:34:18.112 --> 00:34:18.820
planet.
 

00:34:18.820 --> 00:34:23.284
Ecologists have broken the
planet down into areas that

00:34:23.284 --> 00:34:28.338
basically look similar from the
structure of their ecological

00:34:28.338 --> 00:34:31.539
communities,
and are thought to be similar

00:34:31.539 --> 00:34:35.018
in terms of the general control
of ecological processes.

00:34:35.018 --> 00:34:37.530
So you've got ice sheets,
of course.

00:34:37.530 --> 00:34:39.650
Then you've got tundra.
 

00:34:39.650 --> 00:34:43.469
In tundra you normally don't
see plants that are taller than,

00:34:43.469 --> 00:34:45.190
oh, 10 or 20 centimeters.
 

00:34:45.190 --> 00:34:49.527
You have things like dwarf
birch, lots of moss,

00:34:49.527 --> 00:34:51.320
things like that.
 

00:34:51.320 --> 00:34:55.050
Often tundra is overlying
permafrost.

00:34:55.050 --> 00:34:59.552
Then you've got the taiga or
the northern coniferous forests,

00:34:59.552 --> 00:35:03.528
which stretch across much of
the high latitudes in the

00:35:03.528 --> 00:35:05.329
Northern Hemisphere.
 

00:35:05.329 --> 00:35:08.731
You can't really get to these
places in the Southern

00:35:08.731 --> 00:35:09.599
Hemisphere.
 

00:35:09.599 --> 00:35:10.250
Okay?
 

00:35:10.250 --> 00:35:13.572
Antarctica is too cold,
and Africa and Australia don't

00:35:13.572 --> 00:35:15.389
really go far enough south.
 

00:35:15.389 --> 00:35:18.592
There's a little bit of
replication of this in South

00:35:18.592 --> 00:35:22.110
America, but it's mostly a
question there of altitude.

00:35:22.110 --> 00:35:27.673
Then you get some forests that
are extremely similar in Eastern

00:35:27.673 --> 00:35:30.773
North America,
across Western Europe and into

00:35:30.773 --> 00:35:33.929
Central Asia,
and in China and Manchuria,

00:35:33.929 --> 00:35:37.179
which is temperate broadleaf
forest.

00:35:37.179 --> 00:35:41.023
You get similarities in the
rainforests of the Amazon and

00:35:41.023 --> 00:35:45.072
the Congo, and in Southeast
Asia, and in Northern Australia,

00:35:45.072 --> 00:35:46.239
and so forth.
 

00:35:46.239 --> 00:35:50.032
There are, in other words,
these large biomes around the

00:35:50.032 --> 00:35:53.000
planet that are mainly shaped by
climate.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:57.199
And I'm just going to touch
quickly on two of them.

00:35:57.199 --> 00:35:59.800
One of them is the desert biome.
 

00:35:59.800 --> 00:36:05.471
And one tends to find deserts
at about 30 North and about 30

00:36:05.471 --> 00:36:06.239
South.
 

00:36:06.239 --> 00:36:10.257
So, of course,
the Sahara and the Arabian

00:36:10.257 --> 00:36:12.768
Desert are at 30 North.
 

00:36:12.768 --> 00:36:18.440
The deserts of Mexico and
Arizona are at about 30 North.

00:36:18.440 --> 00:36:22.079
The Chilean and Peruvian
deserts, the Atacama Desert,

00:36:22.079 --> 00:36:23.760
are at about 30 South.
 

00:36:23.760 --> 00:36:27.869
The Kalahari and the Namib are
at about 30 South,

00:36:27.869 --> 00:36:33.179
and the Great Central Desert of
Australia is about 30 South.

00:36:33.179 --> 00:36:36.927
And remember,
this is where you have cold air

00:36:36.927 --> 00:36:37.780
falling.
 

00:36:37.780 --> 00:36:39.719
At the equator you have warm
air rising,

00:36:39.719 --> 00:36:42.780
and where you have the deserts
you have cold air falling,

00:36:42.780 --> 00:36:45.170
and there's very little water
in that cold,

00:36:45.170 --> 00:36:47.230
dry air that's falling.
 

00:36:47.230 --> 00:36:49.940
It's quite hot during the day
and it's cold at night.

00:36:49.940 --> 00:36:54.367
So, for example,
if you're in the hot desert of

00:36:54.367 --> 00:36:57.693
Central Australia,
and it's nightfall,

00:36:57.693 --> 00:37:00.989
on a nice clear night the
temperature will go,

00:37:00.989 --> 00:37:04.420
say in Fahrenheit,
from 80 or 90 degrees,

00:37:04.420 --> 00:37:09.280
down to freezing,
in about two or three hours.

00:37:09.280 --> 00:37:12.197
And so Aborigines learn to do
things like all sleep together

00:37:12.197 --> 00:37:13.039
in a big bunch.
 

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:20.476
The wet tropical forests are
about at the equator,

00:37:20.476 --> 00:37:25.063
where you have warm air rising;
warm, moisture-laden air is

00:37:25.063 --> 00:37:25.730
rising.
 

00:37:25.730 --> 00:37:27.250
There are some interesting
twists on that.

00:37:27.250 --> 00:37:29.559
For example,
if you take a packet of air off

00:37:29.559 --> 00:37:32.460
the south Atlantic and you blow
it into the Amazon,

00:37:32.460 --> 00:37:37.302
the Amazon actually will
transpire the moisture in that

00:37:37.302 --> 00:37:39.434
air;
the trees in the Amazon will

00:37:39.434 --> 00:37:42.900
transpire it,
so that by the time a packet of

00:37:42.900 --> 00:37:44.842
rain,
that started here in the south

00:37:44.842 --> 00:37:46.389
Atlantic,
hits the Andes,

00:37:46.389 --> 00:37:48.768
it's been rained out three
times.

00:37:48.768 --> 00:37:50.789
It's gone back up into the
atmosphere, made a cloud;

00:37:50.789 --> 00:37:52.760
gone down into the ground;
gone up into the atmosphere;

00:37:52.760 --> 00:37:53.860
rained out, made a cloud.
 

00:37:53.860 --> 00:37:55.639
And it's done that about,
on the average,

00:37:55.639 --> 00:37:57.599
three times by the time it hits
the Andes.

00:37:57.599 --> 00:38:01.050
So there's some interesting
local stuff going on.

00:38:01.050 --> 00:38:04.932
But roughly speaking,
you find the world's greatest

00:38:04.932 --> 00:38:09.050
biodiversity near the equator in
these rainforests.

00:38:09.050 --> 00:38:11.876
And so if we just take a look
at one of them,

00:38:11.876 --> 00:38:14.510
the Corcovado Rainforest in
Costa Rica;

00:38:14.510 --> 00:38:18.478
and all of you are eligible to
go on an OTS course to Costa

00:38:18.478 --> 00:38:22.719
Rica, and as part of it you'll
probably go to the Corcovado.

00:38:22.719 --> 00:38:26.757
Or, if you were lucky enough to
be in Rick Prum's class this

00:38:26.757 --> 00:38:29.108
semester,
you got taken by Rick,

00:38:29.108 --> 00:38:33.132
over spring break,
to Ecuador, where they logged

00:38:33.132 --> 00:38:36.219
450 species of birds in ten
days.

00:38:36.219 --> 00:38:40.657
And in that kind of habitat you
are going to run into extremely

00:38:40.657 --> 00:38:44.731
high species diversity,
and you're going to see all

00:38:44.731 --> 00:38:49.565
kinds of stuff that you just
never run into in the temperate

00:38:49.565 --> 00:38:50.630
latitudes.
 

00:38:50.630 --> 00:38:54.779
So I strongly recommend a visit
to one of these places,

00:38:54.779 --> 00:38:56.469
if you possibly can.
 

00:38:56.469 --> 00:38:58.980
For a biologist it's pretty
much--this,

00:38:58.980 --> 00:39:04.170
and say going over a coral
reef, especially at night,

00:39:04.170 --> 00:39:06.498
it's kind of like Christmas,
because every time you turn

00:39:06.498 --> 00:39:08.869
around the corner there's
another surprise under the tree

00:39:08.869 --> 00:39:09.969
&gt;
 

00:39:09.969 --> 00:39:13.155
and there's something beautiful
and strange that you've never

00:39:13.155 --> 00:39:13.900
seen before.
 

00:39:13.900 --> 00:39:20.576
So this is the biological
consequence of a long period of

00:39:20.576 --> 00:39:24.175
fairly stable warm,
moist conditions,

00:39:24.175 --> 00:39:27.219
which are the ecological
theater that has allowed this

00:39:27.219 --> 00:39:29.690
kind of evolutionary play to
take place.

00:39:32.599 --> 00:39:36.878
If we look back in time,
there are a couple of things

00:39:36.878 --> 00:39:40.583
about say the last--
this is roughly the last

00:39:40.583 --> 00:39:44.347
fifty-million years,
from the Eocene up to the

00:39:44.347 --> 00:39:47.311
Holocene--
there are a couple of fairly

00:39:47.311 --> 00:39:51.753
neat things that have happened
in terms of the global pattern

00:39:51.753 --> 00:39:52.789
of climate.
 

00:39:52.789 --> 00:39:55.710
One of them is that if you go
back to Eocene,

00:39:55.710 --> 00:39:59.547
when it was really quite warm,
and you had temperate forests

00:39:59.547 --> 00:40:02.280
that went right up to the Arctic
Ocean,

00:40:02.280 --> 00:40:05.324
you can demonstrate that there
were large trees growing in

00:40:05.324 --> 00:40:09.056
Northern Greenland,
at a latitude where it was dark

00:40:09.056 --> 00:40:14.480
for nearly six months a year;
it was warm but it was dark.

00:40:14.480 --> 00:40:17.445
And that really is a rather
interesting comment on what

00:40:17.445 --> 00:40:20.583
trees are capable of;
that you could make a tree that

00:40:20.583 --> 00:40:24.059
would live in complete darkness,
not doing anything for six

00:40:24.059 --> 00:40:27.393
months, and then turn back on
and become actually quite a tall

00:40:27.393 --> 00:40:29.501
forest;
these trees are a meter,

00:40:29.501 --> 00:40:32.559
two meters in diameter,
in Northern Greenland.

00:40:32.559 --> 00:40:35.757
So that's one kind of thing
that the historical look at

00:40:35.757 --> 00:40:37.179
ecology will give you.
 

00:40:37.179 --> 00:40:38.780
But there's another one,
which is really,

00:40:38.780 --> 00:40:42.559
I think, important for everyone
on the planet now,

00:40:42.559 --> 00:40:46.168
and that is that the Eocene,
Oligocene and Miocene were all

00:40:46.168 --> 00:40:48.813
pretty warm;
in fact, they were much warmer

00:40:48.813 --> 00:40:50.530
than the earth currently is.
 

00:40:50.530 --> 00:40:54.135
And when you look say at the
distribution of tropical

00:40:54.135 --> 00:40:57.117
forests--
which is in green--you can see

00:40:57.117 --> 00:41:01.335
that tropical forests covered
really most of the earth for

00:41:01.335 --> 00:41:04.961
tens of millions of years;
and compare that to their

00:41:04.961 --> 00:41:06.030
distribution now.
 

00:41:06.030 --> 00:41:09.465
We're essentially in an
interglacial in the Pleistocene

00:41:09.465 --> 00:41:10.230
right now.
 

00:41:10.230 --> 00:41:13.407
The planet is really much
colder than it has been,

00:41:13.407 --> 00:41:14.250
on average.
 

00:41:14.250 --> 00:41:17.523
